[{"id":"FT4044","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p>Which of the following diagrams best represents the AgNO<sub>3</sub> solution before the reaction occurs?</p>\n\n<p>Note: water molecules are represented by the symbol</p>\n<img alt=\"A figure shows two small circles attached to two large circles on its either side.\" height=\"63\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/e631966465ce74ad097522881c283464/original.png\" width=\"100\">.","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p>The following questions refer to the below.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>M<sup>+</sup> is an unknown metal cation with a +1 charge. A student dissolves the chloride of the unknown metal, MCl, in enough water to make 100.0 mL of solution. The student then mixes the solution with excess AgNO<sub>3</sub> solution, causing AgCl to precipitate. The student collects the precipitate by filtration, dries it, and records the data shown below. (The molar mass of AgCl is 143 g/mol.)</p>\n\n<table class=\"table\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Mass of unknown chloride, MCl</td>\n\t\t\t<td>0.74 g</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Mass of filter paper</td>\n\t\t\t<td>0.80 g</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Mass of filter paper plus AgCl precipitate</td>\n\t\t\t<td>2.23 g</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<img alt=\"Each figures shows multiple water molecules, a sphere labeled A g with a positive one charge, and a larger sphere labeled N O 3 with a negative one charge.  Option A. The sphere labeled A g with a positive one charge is in the top left-hand portion of the figure. Four water molecules are evenly spaced around it. The smaller spheres of the water molecules are pointed away from A g with a positive one charge.  The sphere labeled N O 3 with a negative one charge is in the bottom right-hand portion of the figure. Four water molecules are evenly spaced around it. The smaller spheres of the water molecules are pointed toward N O 3 with a negative one charge. There are 3 other water molecules in the figure.\" height=\"338\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/83f1eb99721f6cc4a2dd2a223448230f/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"Option B. The sphere labeled A g with a positive one charge is in the top left-hand portion of the figure. Four water molecules are evenly spaced around it. The smaller spheres of the water molecules on the above and below are pointed away from A g with a positive one charge and the smaller spheres of the water molecules on the left and right are pointed toward A g with a positive one charge.  The sphere labeled N O 3 with a negative one charge is in the bottom right-hand portion of the figure. Four water molecules are evenly spaced around it. The smaller spheres of the water molecules on the above and bellow are pointed toward N O 3 with a negative one charge and the smaller spheres of the water molecules on the left and right are pointed away from N O 3 with a negative one charge. There are 3 other water molecules in the figure.\" height=\"338\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/67769066eb476a4b873eeadb64d1ee50/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"Option C. The sphere labeled A g with a positive one charge is in the top left-hand portion of the figure. Four water molecules are evenly spaced around it. The smaller spheres of the water molecules are pointed away from A g with a positive one charge.  The sphere labeled N O 3 with a negative one charge is in the bottom right-hand portion of the figure. Four water molecules are evenly spaced around it. The smaller spheres of the water molecules are pointed away from N O 3 with a negative one charge. There are 3 other water molecules in the figure.\" height=\"338\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/f478b3c9b652a1663302744191f5640a/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"Option D. The sphere labeled A g with a positive one charge is touching the larger sphere labeled N O 3 with a negative one charge. There are 11 water molecules in the figure that are scattered around the two labeled spheres.\" height=\"338\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/9bfc7a47abb3d81b033d9d1c66d2e661/original.png\" width=\"200\">"],"answer":-1}]